getting over things when you win.

17:18.436 --> 17:22.396
I guess Sudan is where the press
will make its first hay.

17:22.473 --> 17:26.808
I think if we announce,
the press might have
other things on its mind.

17:26.878 --> 17:31.441
But you know,
Sheldon Runyon and Jack Hathaway
have been friends for years.

17:31.517 --> 17:35.146
And Runyon is going to come after me
with all guns blazing.

17:35.220 --> 17:40.556
Senator, why do we have to worry
about Shelly Runyon's guns
when I control the atomic bomb?

17:40.626 --> 17:44.756
We'll introduce you
to the Cabinet in one hour.
I'll make the announcement then.

17:44.830 --> 17:47.856
- That's fine, Mr. President.
- That's the wayJerry Ford
did it with Rockefeller.

17:47.933 --> 17:50.993
I always thought it was pretty damn
classy. Have we notified the networks?

17:51.070 --> 17:54.562
Oh, yes. All the pundits
are in a guessing feeding frenzy.

17:54.640 --> 17:58.076
Box of Malomars says
they've already anointed Malloy.

17:58.143 --> 18:02.170
- You look great, by the way. Just great.
- Thank you, sir.

18:02.247 --> 18:06.809
Okay, guys, one hour,
the Cabinet Room.

18:06.885 --> 18:09.285
<i>Off to the races! </i>

18:09.354 --> 18:13.017
- Senator, is this
what you're gonna wear?
- She looks fine.

18:13.092 --> 18:15.356
- No, she does.
- You look beautiful, Senator.

18:15.427 --> 18:17.452
- Thank you.
- Very becoming.

18:17.529 --> 18:19.463
I think it works.

18:19.832 --> 18:21.595
Let me explain
how this is gonna work.

18:21.667 --> 18:24.192
In a minute, POTUS is gonna come in,
make an announcement...

18:24.269 --> 18:27.261
- Introduce you
to the vice presidential designate.
<i>-Jerry. </i>

18:27.339 --> 18:30.570
We hear the president's decision
is Malloy. Can you confirm this?

18:30.642 --> 18:34.510
In ten seconds you're gonna have
your answer. So calm down.

18:34.580 --> 18:39.017
All right. Then after he's made...
Dave. [Whispers]

18:39.084 --> 18:42.247
I'm gonna give you guys
20 minutes for questions and answers.

18:42.321 --> 18:45.085
So keep them short
and, hopefully, sweet.

18:45.157 --> 18:47.591
And you can roll starting now.

18:47.659 --> 18:50.856
I'll introduce him
in five... thousand...

18:50.929 --> 18:55.832
four... thousand,
three... thousand, two.

18:55.901 --> 18:59.837
Ladies and gentlemen,
the president of the United States.

19:03.242 --> 19:07.144
Welcome. Good afternoon.
Please.

19:07.212 --> 19:11.945
- Thank you for coming here
on such short notice.
<i>- Laine Hanson, from Ohio. </i>

19:12.017 --> 19:15.919
As I embarked on the task
of selecting a vice president...

19:15.988 --> 19:18.752
I was driven by the emotion
of wanting to make a choice...

19:18.824 --> 19:22.453
that would've made Troy Ellard,
my friend, proud.

19:22.528 --> 19:26.555
Senator Laine Billings Hanson
of Ohio is that person.

19:26.632 --> 19:28.725
<i>[Toliver]</i>
<i>Sherri, you are first. </i>

19:28.800 --> 19:34.102
<i>Ms. Hanson, do you feel being</i>
<i>a woman played any type of role</i>
<i>in the president's decision? </i>

19:34.173 --> 19:37.768
Well, l, uh...
First I would like to say...

19:37.843 --> 19:41.540
what an honor it is to be here
before you in this position.

19:41.613 --> 19:46.073
And I hope to serve up to the
standards which President Evans
set for me in that introduction.

19:46.151 --> 19:49.917
Thank you so much, sir.
To answer your question...

19:49.988 --> 19:54.152
- First rate, Mrs. Hanson.
- Thank you. I learned
a lot from Will.

19:54.226 --> 19:56.854
Ah, yes, Will.

19:56.929 --> 19:58.920
You, sir, are gonna have
to make yourself scarce.

19:58.997 --> 20:03.661
- No, of course.
I'll give you your privacy.
- No, I mean scarce.

20:03.735 --> 20:05.999
During the confirmation period,
I want you out of sight.

20:06.071 --> 20:08.733
- Pardon me?
<i>-A wife there behind her husband... </i>

20:08.807 --> 20:11.173
is perceived as supportive.

20:11.243 --> 20:16.340
A husband following around behind
his wife is perceived as a puppeteer.

20:16.415 --> 20:18.975
- But I think...
- No, honey. I think
Mr. Newman's right on.

20:19.051 --> 20:20.985
Let Hollis handle
the day-to-day...

20:21.053 --> 20:23.749
- And I'll be the man behind the curtain.
- Where do we go from here?

20:23.822 --> 20:27.952
<i>The FBI's gonna have to do</i>
<i>an extensive background check. </i>

20:28.026 --> 20:31.427
- Director Friend
will handle the investigation.
- Yes, we made sure of that.

20:31.496 --> 20:34.795
<i>Just about every aspect of your life</i>
<i>will be uncovered. </i>

20:34.866 --> 20:37.960
Your bank accounts,
your medical reports.

20:38.036 --> 20:41.301
- What am I forgetting?
<i>- Correspondence to</i>
<i>government agencies, speeches... </i>

20:41.373 --> 20:45.810
When Nelson Rockefeller was confirmed,
they had over 300 agents working on him.

20:45.877 --> 20:49.142
They had a lot more life
and cash to investigate, huh?

20:49.214 --> 20:53.310
<i>We'll do our own background</i>
<i>check in case anything falls</i>
<i>through the cracks, to be safe. </i>

20:53.385 --> 20:57.344
- At the same time,
the House will... Come in.
<i>-[Knocking At Door]</i>

20:57.422 --> 20:59.982
The House will put together
its bipartisan subcommittee...

21:00.058 --> 21:04.290
of theJudiciary to interview you and
advise and consent to your nomination.

21:04.363 --> 21:06.695
Shelly Runyon's
running the show there.

21:06.765 --> 21:10.724
Cheyenne, Wyoming, you're on with
Vice President Designate Laine Hanson.

21:10.802 --> 21:13.168
- [Man] Larry, how are you?
- I'm fine. Thanks for calling.

21:13.238 --> 21:16.469
I just wanted to say
to the senator that...

21:16.541 --> 21:18.668
all of Cheyenne is with her.

21:18.744 --> 21:22.680
We think she's absolutely great for
the country and this administration.

21:22.748 --> 21:25.774
- Congratulations.
- [King] What's the question, sir?

21:25.851 --> 21:29.810
<i>I wanted to ask the senator, if she</i>
<i>could pick one person from history... </i>

21:29.888 --> 21:33.517
<i>to serve as her model for how to behave</i>
<i>in office, who would that be? </i>

21:33.592 --> 21:36.322
<i>-[Knock At Door]</i>
<i>-[King] Good question, Senator. </i>

21:36.395 --> 21:40.331
<i>Hey, guys. </i>
<i>Nice to see you. </i>

21:40.399 --> 21:45.496
<i>-Sorry to barge in on you. </i>
- No, no, no, no.
I'm just watching your girl.

21:45.570 --> 21:49.062
- First female prime ministers?
- They were great leaders.

21:49.141 --> 21:51.268
Would you put Thatcher
in that category?

21:51.343 --> 21:53.675
No, I don't think so.

21:53.745 --> 21:57.681
- You know what? I would
have to say Thomas Jefferson.
- [King] A man?

21:57.749 --> 22:00.650
<i>-She's something, isn't she? </i>
- I don't really know her.

22:00.719 --> 22:05.088
We served together
a few years ago, and, I guess...

22:05.157 --> 22:08.217
we just ended up
in different company.

22:08.293 --> 22:12.195
- Take a seat.
<i>- Congressman, the president</i>
<i>asked us to come down here. </i>

22:12.264 --> 22:15.791
<i>He'd like to let you know</i>
<i>he'd appreciate your support</i>
<i>in the senator's confirmation. </i>

22:15.867 --> 22:21.134
- Really?
<i>- He asked me directly, Shell. </i>

22:21.206 --> 22:24.039
But the president didn't consider it
important enough to ask me personally?

22:24.109 --> 22:27.875
<i>You know it's important. </i>
<i>It's the old man's swan song. </i>

22:27.946 --> 22:30.540
<i>Putting a woman in office</i>
<i>means something to him. </i>

22:30.615 --> 22:33.379
Laine Hanson's
the absolute best choice.

22:33.452 --> 22:38.412
You don't believe that.
Come on. You're too smart.

22:38.490 --> 22:41.118
Look, I don't mind
she's a woman...

22:41.193 --> 22:45.562
but I'm not confirming a woman
just because she's a woman.

22:45.630 --> 22:48.622
Laine Hanson
has an extra burden.

22:48.700 --> 22:51.897
She's has to come on the world stage
with perfect credentials.

22:51.970 --> 22:54.165
Margaret Thatcher didn't have perfect
credentials. The world respected her.

22:54.239 --> 22:58.676
The world accepted Margaret Thatcher
because they knew she had to answer
to Ronald Reagan.

22:58.744 --> 23:03.272
A woman better be pretty damn qualified
to have nobody to answer to...

23:03.348 --> 23:07.842
and Laine Hanson
is not that.

23:07.919 --> 23:10.683
Look me in the eyes
and tell me...

23:10.756 --> 23:15.420
that Laine Hanson is your first choice
for the vice presidency.

23:17.396 --> 23:20.923
Laine Hanson
is my absolute first choice.

23:23.568 --> 23:26.093
I'd so want you
in my poker game.

23:31.042 --> 23:33.602
Country needs
a smooth confirmation.

23:33.678 --> 23:35.612
The president needs
a smooth confirmation.

23:35.680 --> 23:39.343
- The country needs
a competent vice president.
<i>-[Cell Phone Ringing]</i>

23:39.418 --> 23:41.784
Excuse me a minute.

23:41.853 --> 23:45.846
There's only one person in the world
that has that phone number.

23:45.924 --> 23:50.054
So who's the second choice?

23:50.128 --> 23:52.790
We haven't really settled
on anybody yet.

23:52.864 --> 23:56.891
Tell me, if Laine Hanson were
to be hit by a flying car...

23:56.968 --> 23:59.562
who would the president
then select?

24:01.339 --> 24:03.330
[Sighs]

24:03.408 --> 24:06.707
I think the president
still likes Jack Hathaway, Congressman.

24:13.218 --> 24:14.845
<i>You know... </i>

24:14.920 --> 24:19.516
Jack Hathaway, there's a good man...
for a Democrat.

24:19.591 --> 24:23.288
[Laughs] There's a man
I would say would have...

24:23.361 --> 24:26.057
a smooth confirmation.

24:26.131 --> 24:28.725
- Jack Hathaway?
- Smooth as a baby's ass.

24:28.800 --> 24:32.463
- He's already taken himself
out of it, so...
<i>- Right. </i>

24:32.537 --> 24:35.028
Right!
Well, who the hell knows?

24:35.106 --> 24:38.371
Perhaps Lainey
will shock the world...

24:38.443 --> 24:40.673
by pulling out
her brilliance...

24:40.745 --> 24:43.441
<i>and erudition at the hearings</i>
<i>that none of us know she has. </i>

24:43.515 --> 24:46.177
So, Shelly, can we ask
for basic fairness?

24:46.251 --> 24:50.779
<i>- Fifty-fifty, Democrat and</i>
<i>Republican at the hearings? </i>
- Of course you can.

25:01.766 --> 25:05.293
Congressman! Congressman!
Mr. Runyon.

25:05.370 --> 25:08.498
Just wanted to steal you
for a second. I'm Reg Webster.

25:08.573 --> 25:12.942
- Oh, you're one of Stoney's boys?
- Uh, no.

25:13.011 --> 25:15.138
You staff or intern?

25:15.213 --> 25:18.649
Actually I'm a representative.
Reginald Webster of Delaware.

25:18.717 --> 25:22.175
Oh, fuck me. I'm sorry, Webster.
What can I do for you?

25:22.254 --> 25:26.520
- I'm running late.
- I was hoping I could grab
your attention for a second.

25:26.591 --> 25:29.822
- What's the skinny?
- Well, uh...

25:29.895 --> 25:34.764
- I'm late, Mr. Webster.
- I understand a chair's
opened up in the committee...

25:34.833 --> 25:36.858
and I'd like
to put my name forward.

25:36.935 --> 25:39.665
I believe you'll find me
industrious and hardworking.

25:39.738 --> 25:43.105
TheJudiciary's
for senior members.

25:43.174 --> 25:46.632
Wheeling was in for five terms
before we let him in.

25:46.711 --> 25:49.179
My hands are tied.
There's nothing I can do.

25:49.247 --> 25:51.807
Shelly, I've been trying
to reach you for five days.

25:51.883 --> 25:55.046
- I left you 3 2 messages.
- Well, leave me a 33rd.

25:55.120 --> 25:57.953
- Where you from?
- Delaware.

25:58.023 --> 26:02.323
Oh, yeah, you were...
You knocked Emory Bettis out.

26:02.394 --> 26:05.022
Emory used to be
in the Thursday night game.

26:05.096 --> 26:07.656
He was always good
for a few hundred bucks.

26:07.732 --> 26:10.257
I guess he ran his campaign
like he played poker.

26:10.335 --> 26:14.499
I take it you have
a predisposition.

26:14.573 --> 26:18.839
- About the confirmation, I mean.
- No. Actually, I'm 100% objective.

26:18.910 --> 26:22.107
- Mmm. Do you have
a dictionary, Mr. Webster?
- Yeah.

26:22.180 --> 26:25.775
Take a Magic Marker,
cross out the word "objectivity."

26:25.850 --> 26:30.753
Your constituents want you
for your opinions, your philosophy...

26:30.822 --> 26:33.484
for your subjectivity.

26:38.930 --> 26:41.797
Laver has to duck
out of the way of that one.

26:41.866 --> 26:45.734
<i>One that Laver can't get. </i>
<i>He's still trying to recover. </i>

26:48.173 --> 26:51.540
And he zings another
powerful forehand past Laver.

26:51.610 --> 26:53.976
See that, Tim-Tim?
Know what we call that?

26:54.045 --> 26:57.378
- We call that topspin.
You know how we get topspin?
- Uh-huh.

26:57.449 --> 27:00.646
<i>- Yeah? Tell me. </i>
- 'Cause BabyJesus made topspin.

27:00.719 --> 27:02.653
<i>What? </i>

27:02.721 --> 27:05.155
<i>- BabyJesus gave it topspin. </i>
- Jesus?

27:05.223 --> 27:07.851
Ah! Why do you say that?

27:07.926 --> 27:12.556
- Because BabyJesus made everything.
- Yeah? Who told you that?

27:12.631 --> 27:15.099
<i>Miss Moyer in kindergarten, </i>
<i>and Mommy says... </i>

27:15.166 --> 27:18.693
<i>- I have to listen Miss Moyer. </i>
- Wow, this is news to me.

27:18.770 --> 27:23.173
I gave up my career
trying to strike that nonsense
out of the public school system.

27:23.241 --> 27:25.539
Maybe I ought to put him
in public school, then.

27:25.610 --> 27:27.544
Remember what I told you
about moving your grip down...

27:27.612 --> 27:30.172
- And to the left?
- Uh-huh.

27:30.248 --> 27:33.513
- Go see if Dad's found
his bathing suit yet.
- Gimme a hug.

27:35.787 --> 27:38.051
Yeah. Thanks, champ.

27:43.428 --> 27:47.159
- They are paid to teach, not...
- To preach.

27:47.232 --> 27:50.531
I know, but he's six years old, and he
also believes in the tooth fairy...

27:50.602 --> 27:55.198
- And that George Washington
never told a lie.
- Well, it drives me crazy.

27:55.273 --> 27:58.333
- Mary, wanna turn the ball machine off?
<i>- Yes, Mr. Governor. </i>

28:02.180 --> 28:04.114
Thanks for seeing me, Dad.

28:04.182 --> 28:06.616
- Why wouldn't I see you?
- Partisanship.

28:06.685 --> 28:10.280
I gotta love
at least one Democrat.

28:13.391 --> 28:18.988
You know, Dad, I'm getting some reports
that you might not be ready to back me.

28:19.064 --> 28:21.555
That you're opposed
to my confirmation...

28:21.633 --> 28:23.430
- You've heard quotes?
- No, I haven't heard.

28:23.501 --> 28:26.231
Just that we should expect
to be reading of your opposition.

28:26.304 --> 28:29.102
Pardon my Swahili, but you're being led
a line of pure bullshit.

28:29.174 --> 28:34.578
- I haven't said a word.
<i>- Maybe it's just that. </i>
<i>Maybe you've been quiet. </i>

28:34.646 --> 28:37.342
- I hate the press.
<i>- I know, Dad. </i>

28:37.415 --> 28:40.942
- When I left the mansion,
I swore I would never talk to them.
<i>- I remember. </i>

28:41.019 --> 28:46.184
- I suppose you're gonna force
my hand on this, huh?
- You wouldn't have to say much.

28:46.257 --> 28:48.248
- Just a little something.
- Okay, okay.

28:48.326 --> 28:51.693
l, uh...

28:51.763 --> 28:53.924
I'll call back
Joe Glynn at the <i>Times. </i>

28:53.998 --> 28:56.523
He's okay.
He'll write it up well.

28:56.601 --> 28:59.297
I once leaked him
some shit about Buchanan.
Damn near won him the Pulitzer.

28:59.370 --> 29:01.702
- Thanks, Dad.
- Sure.

29:01.773 --> 29:03.707
Thanks.

29:03.775 --> 29:07.404
What would you do,
or have done, in my case?

29:07.479 --> 29:11.779
Well, when your president
asks you to jump...

29:11.850 --> 29:14.341
it's hard not to jump,
that's for sure.

29:14.419 --> 29:17.115
But you remember what Ben Franklin
said about the vice presidency.

29:17.188 --> 29:19.952
What did he say?
I didn't talk to him this week.

29:20.024 --> 29:24.984
He said he ought to be addressed as
"Your Superfluous Excellency."

29:25.063 --> 29:28.396
In the past ten years,
I've enjoyed the kind of power
the vice presidency can't offer.

29:28.466 --> 29:31.026
Why would anybody want
to give that up? Am I crazy?

29:31.102 --> 29:34.594
Baby, power is
where power goes.

29:34.672 --> 29:37.971
- Think you can beat me?
- Uh, yeah. Okay.

29:38.042 --> 29:40.909
Hey, Tony!

29:40.979 --> 29:43.447
Foul!

29:43.515 --> 29:47.315
Can't trust
those fuckin' people.

29:47.385 --> 29:52.254
Speaking of which, Mr. Webster,
it turns out you're a Democrat.

29:52.323 --> 29:55.724
l, uh, wasn't keeping it
a secret.

29:55.794 --> 30:00.231
Sad to say, I don't think I can
bring you aboard the committee, son.

30:00.298 --> 30:04.064
<i>Ray Spies makes all the decisions</i>
<i>regarding the other party. </i>

30:04.135 --> 30:06.262
<i>- It's a courtesy. </i>
- But not a requirement.

30:06.337 --> 30:09.067
- It's not, that's true.
<i>- If Ray Spies interviewed me... </i>

30:09.140 --> 30:11.631
he'd refuse to put me
on the committee even for a minute...

30:11.709 --> 30:13.768
because he'd find out that
when it comes to Laine Hanson...

30:13.845 --> 30:16.336
I went to my dictionary
and crossed off the word "objectivity."

30:16.414 --> 30:21.113
Are you suggesting Mrs. Hanson may not
be your first choice for vice president?

30:21.186 --> 30:25.418
I'm suggesting that Laine Hanson
has stricken our party
with policies and attitudes...

30:25.490 --> 30:28.357
that are best served
across the aisle from where she came.

30:28.426 --> 30:31.953
I take it, like most
members of your party...

30:32.030 --> 30:35.227
your selection would be
Governor Hathaway.

30:35.300 --> 30:37.291
Governor Hathaway's a great man.

30:37.368 --> 30:41.065
He's a visionary,
a bona fide hero.

30:41.139 --> 30:45.473
- But he withdrew his name
from consideration.
- Minds can be changed.

30:45.543 --> 30:50.207
- How much discretion
can I count on from you?
- A hundred percent, sir.

30:50.281 --> 30:52.511
- Even from your own leadership?
- I said a hundred percent.

30:52.584 --> 30:57.317
Good. Good man.
Good man.

30:57.388 --> 31:01.119
I think if I make the rounds,
do the Sunday morning talk shows...

31:01.192 --> 31:04.525
raise the level of the game a bit,
outtalk her on the issues...

31:04.596 --> 31:09.363
Issues? What kind of fucking campaigns
are they running in Virginia?

31:09.434 --> 31:13.165
Not the kind I'm used to.
Jack, this whole thing
with the girl drowning...

31:13.238 --> 31:15.172
It's bullshit!

31:15.240 --> 31:18.403
- I was there, Shelly.
The president told me himself.
<i>- It's an excuse. </i>

31:18.476 --> 31:23.140
Jackson Evans has chosen to make
putting a woman in office his swan song.

31:23.214 --> 31:26.843
<i>Laine Hanson is the only</i>
<i>reasonable choice in your party. </i>

31:26.918 --> 31:30.479
He's not going with Boxer.
She's too liberal.

31:30.555 --> 31:33.456
He's not going with Jones
because she's older than he is.

31:33.524 --> 31:36.584
- There's Winslet.
- She's not coming off
the Supreme Court.

31:36.661 --> 31:40.461
<i>Laine Hanson is attractive. </i>
<i>She's a looker. </i>

31:40.531 --> 31:44.729
The mere fact that she was
a Republican means that she
can't be too far to the left.

31:44.802 --> 31:46.827
It's a perfect pedigree.

31:46.905 --> 31:51.342
We can't get you in by convincing him
you're the right man for the job.

31:51.409 --> 31:55.778
We have to convince him that
she's wrong. Once we do that, you're in.

31:55.847 --> 31:58.714
And Toliver,
he's as much as told me...

31:58.783 --> 32:00.944
I'm not going for a low blow.
It's not my way.

32:01.019 --> 32:02.987
You won't have to.

32:03.054 --> 32:06.023
<i>We have to go after her. We have</i>
<i>to make her wade in her own blood. </i>

32:06.090 --> 32:08.991
- Who did you say you were?
- I'm Makerowitz.

32:09.060 --> 32:11.824
- Makerowitz.
<i>- I'm sorry. That doesn't</i>
<i>mean much to me. </i>

32:11.896 --> 32:15.093
- Web got somebody...
- A friend of the Hathaway campaign.

32:15.166 --> 32:17.964
Who is footing the not-too-unimpressive
bill of Mr. Makerowitz.

32:18.036 --> 32:19.970
<i>Private citizen wants to do</i>
<i>their own investigation... </i>

32:20.038 --> 32:24.839
What exactly are you trying to find out?
Campaign irregularities, bribes?

32:24.909 --> 32:26.934
- Isn't that the FBI's responsibility?
- Yes, it is.

